          "prompt_html": "<h1>NOTE COMPLETION 64</h1><p><strong>Questions 31 - 40</strong></p><p>Complete the notes.</p><p>Use <strong>NO MORE THAN ONE WORD</strong> for each answer.</p><p><strong>A history of measuring time</strong></p><p>Measuring the time in a year or a day has always been a priority</p><p>People in ancient civilisations had sophisticated <blank data-qid=\"q31\"/>  to record the passing of time</p><p><strong>Some ancient tools for measuring time</strong></p><p>Stonehenge: a 5000-year-old stone circle in England</p><p>It was possibly built by druids (priests)</p><p>The stones seem to have been erected for viewing the <blank data-qid=\"q32\"/> on the solstice (the longest day of the year).</p><p>In the past, days were divided into 12 periods</p><p>Shadow clocks have been discovered in <blank data-qid=\"q33\"/> , which consisted of a large column</p><p>Some were constructed out of <blank data-qid=\"q34\"/> , and were several metres in height</p><p><strong>Water clocks</strong></p><p>These were used in various locations and had moving parts</p><p>However, they were ineffective in <blank data-qid=\"q35\"/> conditions</p><p>Engineers in China addressed this problem by using mercury and <blank data-qid=\"q36\"/></p><p>instead of water</p><p><strong>Mechanical clocks</strong></p><p>The first known one was constructed in Germany in the 10th century</p><p>In the 14th century, a clock with a <blank data-qid=\"q37\"/></p><p>to mark the hours was constructed; this is still in Salisbury Cathedral, England</p><p><strong>Further developments in clock making</strong></p><p>Clockmakers aimed to produce clocks that were <blank data-qid=\"q38\"/></p><p>and able to tell the time more precisely, especially to aid sailors with navigation</p><p>Thomas Tompion, an English clockmaker, managed to produce a clock that was small enough to be <blank data-qid=\"q39\"/></p><p>Tompion gave one of these to an English <blank data-qid=\"q40\"/></p>",
